  "prompt": "How are the writings of \"kt\" and \"tta\" from each other? They look the same from this site.",
  "response": "The writings of \"kt\" and \"tta\" may appear similar at first glance, especially in certain fonts or handwriting styles, but they are distinct sequences of letters. Here's how to differentiate them:\n\n1. **\"kt\"**:\n   - Consists of the letters \"k\" followed by \"t.\"\n   - The \"k\" is a single letter with a straight vertical line and a diagonal stroke.\n   - The \"t\" is another single letter with a vertical line and a horizontal crossbar.\n\n2. **\"tta\"**:\n   - Consists of the letters \"t\" followed by another \"t\" and then \"a.\"\n   - The first \"t\" is the same as in \"kt.\"\n   - The second \"t\" is identical to the first.\n   - The \"a\" is a distinct letter with a rounded shape, often resembling a circle with a tail.\n\n**Key Differences**:\n- **Number of Letters**: \"kt\" has two letters, while \"tta\" has three.\n- **Sequence**: \"kt\" ends with a \"t,\" while \"tta\" starts with two \"t\"s and ends with an \"a.\"\n- **Visual Appearance**: The \"a\" in \"tta\" makes it visually distinct from \"kt.\"\n\nIf they look the same on the site you're using, it might be due to the font or spacing. Adjusting the font or zooming in could help you see the differences more clearly.",
